 me=\r\nrely intellectual. &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Only with repeated actions does knowledge get i=\r\nngrained in one&#39;s &lt;BR&gt;&gt; consciousness so deeply that all of one&#39;s instin=\r\ncts, thoughts and deeds &lt;BR&gt;&gt; are shaped by that correct knowledge (inst=\r\nead of underlying &lt;BR&gt;&gt; conditioning). Just &quot;knowing&quot; intellectually tha=\r\nt a movie is not real &lt;BR&gt;&gt; and there is no need to take what happens on=\r\n the screen seriously is not &lt;BR&gt;&gt; enough to stop you from getting start=\r\nled when a really scary scene comes &lt;BR&gt;&gt; in the movie! You need to prac=\r\ntice a lot before that knowledge becomes &lt;BR&gt;&gt; natural and permanent and=\r\n you stop getting startled.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Similarly, actionss without kn=\r\nowledge are useless too.\n One keeps &lt;BR&gt;&gt; performing actions forever the=\r\nn. One watching a movie 1000 times without &lt;BR&gt;&gt; the knowledge that it i=\r\ns unreal and should not be taken seriously will &lt;BR&gt;&gt; get startled each =\r\ntime and enjoy the experience.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; In http://tinyurl.com/homam=\r\nwhy document (from WAVES 2010 conference), I &lt;BR&gt;&gt; gave an analogy. Supp=\r\nose one needs to walk to the top of a mountain. One &lt;BR&gt;&gt; with gyaana bu=\r\nt no karma is like a person standing at the base and &lt;BR&gt;&gt; staring at th=\r\ne pinnacle. He knows where to go, but he will remain at the &lt;BR&gt;&gt; base f=\r\norever. One with karma but no gyaana is like a person going around &lt;BR&gt;&gt;=\r\n the mountain forever. One balancing karma and gyana, i.e. engaging in &lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&gt; actions cocupled with the correct understanding that all is Brahman, i=\r\ns &lt;BR&gt;&gt; like a person climbing the mountain and watching the top from ti=\r\nme to &lt;BR&gt;&gt; time to correct one&#39;s course. He will eventually reach the p=\r\ninnacle. &lt;BR&gt;&gt;\n Karma and gyaana need to go hand in hand and are definit=\r\nely not &lt;BR&gt;&gt; opposites or alternatives.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; is free f=\r\nrom all the faults of samsaraf samsara, one does not find any &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt;=\r\n benefit out&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; of actions which he has done or which he has to d=\r\no.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Actions with attachment (i.e. actions with agyaana) can=\r\n be criticized &lt;BR&gt;&gt; and dismissed. But detached actions (i.e. actions w=\r\nith gyaana) should be &lt;BR&gt;&gt; encouraged.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;=\r\nBR&gt;&gt; This equating of liberation and spiritual progress with akarma &lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&gt; (inaction), instead of detached action (nishkaama karma), is what led =\r\nto &lt;BR&gt;&gt; the temporary downfall of Sanatana Dharma in the world. This is=\r\n &lt;BR&gt;&gt; pseudo-Vedanta and not the real deal.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; As long as=\r\n you self-identify with a body, desires arise from time to &lt;BR&gt;&gt; time. T=\r\nhe purer your conditioning is, the more dharmik those desires &lt;BR&gt;&gt; will=\r\n be.\n Perform the best action within your capability to fulfil those &lt;BR&gt;&g=\r\nt; desires. Once action is done, surrender it to the Lord and do not think =\r\n&lt;BR&gt;&gt; about it anymore. Whatever result comes, take it as God&#39;s will and=\r\n do &lt;BR&gt;&gt; not regret or rejoice. No pride and no shame. As you do this m=\r\nore and &lt;BR&gt;&gt; more, your conditioning will drop more and more and your c=\r\nonsciousness &lt;BR&gt;&gt; will become purer and purer. Your conscience will spe=\r\nak louder and &lt;BR&gt;&gt; louder and your sense of dharma will be refined. You=\r\nr desires will &lt;BR&gt;&gt; become more and more dharmik. You will transition f=\r\nrom fulfilling dharma &lt;BR&gt;&gt; towards individual self to fulfilling dharma=\r\n towards universal self. &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Eventually, you will reach a stage where =\r\nyou perform actions with no &lt;BR&gt;&gt; identification. Then action become non=\r\n-action.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Vishnu, Shiva, rishis etc also do not engage in i=\r\nnaction. Instead, they &lt;BR&gt;&gt; engage in detached action for maintaining\n =\r\nand supporting the Cosmic &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Order, as determined by the Supreme Cosm=\r\nic Being and His Shakti (his &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Kinetic aspect).&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * *=\r\n *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; One acts only when there is desire. A desireless m=\r\nan, whose desires &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; have been&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; fulfilled, who has r=\r\nisen above desires, whose desire is the atman, has &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; no&lt;BR&gt;&gt;=\r\n &gt; necessity to act.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; First of all, everybody whose self=\r\n-identification with a body remains &lt;BR&gt;&gt; atleast to a small extent IS p=\r\nerforming actions continually. At the bare &lt;BR&gt;&gt; minimum, one performs a=\r\nctions like breathing, eating, drinking water, &lt;BR&gt;&gt; urinating and defec=\r\nating, which affect the lives of millions of &lt;BR&gt;&gt; micro-organisms.&lt;BR&gt;&=\r\ngt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; Second, one &quot;whose desire is the atman&quot; still needs to perform=\r\n actions &lt;BR&gt;&gt; to fulfil that desire and be established in atman always.=\r\n Running away &lt;BR&gt;&gt; from actions and samsara will not free one\n from sam=\r\nsara.&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; * * *&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; Sannyasa is absolutely n=\r\necessary whether it be vividisha-sannyasa or &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; vidvat-sannyasa.=\r\n&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; Without perfect renunciation it is impossible to pursue the p=\r\nath of &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; Brahmavidya. ...&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; it is foolish to cite in=\r\nstances of Janaka and others who did not take &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; sannyasa but&lt;BR=\r\n&gt;&gt; &gt; possessed Brahmajnana. Such instances are quoted by householders=\r\n who &lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; are unwilling&lt;BR&gt;&gt; &gt; to leave th